						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">rizz1010 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Ah, so you can’t have a generic 8KB bank and choose later whether it goes into $8000 or $A000?</div><br />Well, actually you can put the banks in any slot you want, but if you <strong>.base</strong> a bank at $A000 and load it at $8000 the labels will be all screwed up. For example, if you create the following bank:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; &nbsp;.base $a000<br /><br />SomeTable: .db $45, $6b, $80<br /><br />&nbsp; &nbsp;.pad $bfff</div><br />But instead of mapping it at $a000 you load it at $8000, when you try to access that table it will not work, because the label "SomeTable" translates to $A000, and who knows what will be mapped there.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">This has to be predetermined?  (not that it will matter – just interested in learning)</div><br />If you know what you are doing and you actually have a reason to do it, you can load the same bank in different slots, just be careful with the labels.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Building on your example, would this work:</div><br />Looks fine to me.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Does it matter which order you use the .base directive?  Can you use .base $C000 ahead of .base $8000 in your file?</div>
<br />The order doesn't matter, you can do it like that.</div>

